f the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":67,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":76,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Kitenore was born about 1148, in Henley-on-Thames, Oxfordshire, England as the daughter of Adam of Kitenore. She had at least 2 sons with Sir William Malet Of Enmore. She died in 1237, in Enmore Castle, Somerset, England, at the age of 90."},"et":{"about 1148–1237":"umbes 1148–1237","1148–1237":"1148–1237","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","1176–Male":"1176–Surnud","1178–1256":"1178–1256","–Male":"Surnud","1237":"1237","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1256":"1256","1178":"1178","1145":"1145","1176":"1176","about 1148":"umbes 1148","England":"England","Enmore, Somerse